'''Christopher John Kitching''' [[Commander of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 5 August 1955) is a British [[archivist]] who formerly served as Secretary of the [[Historical Manuscripts Commission]] (part of the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|National Archives]]) from 1992-2004.<ref name="chriskitching">{{cite web |title=Kitching, Christopher John, (born 5 Aug. 1945), Secretary, Historical Manuscripts Commission |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-23270?rskey=nNakhs&result=122 |website=UK Who's Who |accessdate=4 October 2018 |language=en |}}</ref>
Kitching completed a Bachelor of Arts in Modern History at [[Durham University]] in 1967, followed by a PhD at the same institution in 1970.<ref>{{cite web |title=XVIII (ns), supplement |url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=bookreader/DU_Gazettes/DUGazette18_3/dg183METS.xml#page/26/mode/2up |website=Durham University Gazette |accessdate=4 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He was awarded the ''Alexander Prize'' from the [[Royal Historical Society]] in 1973.<ref name=chriskitching /> He began his career as an Assistant Keeper at the [[Public Record Office]], where he worked until 1982, before joining the [[Royal Commission on Historic Monuments]] as an Assistant Secretary.<ref name=chriskitching /> He served in this role until 1992, upon which he joined The National Archives.<ref name=chriskitching />
