{{Infobox person | name = Howqua | image = Howqua, 1830.jpg | image_size = 250px | alt = | caption = Portrait by [[George Chinnery]], 1830 | birth_name = Wu Bingjian | birth_date = 1769 | birth_place = [[Fujian]], [[Qing Dynasty|China]] | death_date = 4 September 1843 (age 75) | death_place = [[Guangzhou|Canton]], China | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | residence = | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | other_names = | known_for = Founder of [[Cohong]] - Ewo (怡和) | education = | alma_mater = | employer = | notable works = | occupation = | years_active = | home_town = | salary = | net worth = Over $8 billion | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relations = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | footnotes = | box_width = | misc = }} {{Infobox Chinese|pic=Howqua.png|picsize=200px|piccap=Portrait by [[Lam Qua]]|showflag=cp|c=伍秉鑑|p=Wǔ Bǐngjiàn|mi={{IPAc-cmn|wu|3|-|b|ing|3|j|ian|4}}|myr=Wǔ Bǐngjyàn|w=Wu Ping-chien|j=Ng5 Bing2 Gaam3|y=Ngh Bíng Gaam|poj=Ngó͘ Péng-kàm|ci={{IPA-yue|ŋ̬̍ pɪ̌ŋ kāːm|}}|altname=Business name|c2=浩官|p2=Hào Guān|myr2=Hàu Gwān|w2=Hao Kuan|poj2=Hō-koaⁿ|j2=Hou6 Gun1|y2=Houh Gūn|ci2={{IPA-yue|hòu kúːn|}}}}
'''Howqua''' (1769{{spaced ndash}}4 September 1843<ref>Hunt, Freeman; Dana, William B. (1844). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=trtJAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA459 The Merchants' Magazine and Commercial Review]''. Volume 10. p. 459.</ref>) was the most important of the Hong merchants in the [[Thirteen Factories]], head of the ''[[Ewo (hong)|E-wo hong]]'' and leader of the Canton [[Cohong]]. He was once one of the richest men in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Rich-How-They-That-Time/dp/0812932676/133-3377470-4449360?_encoding=UTF8&%2AVersion%2A=1&%2Aentries%2A=0|title=The Rich and How They Got That Way: How the Wealthiest People of All Time--from Genghis Khan to Bill Gates--Made Their Fortunes|date=2 October 2018|website=Amazon.ca|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>''The Rich And How They Got That Way'' By Cynthia Crossen Publisher: Crown Publishing Group Pub. Date: 2000 {{ISBN|0-8129-3267-6}}</ref><ref name="chinareviewnews.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinareviewnews.com/doc/1008/1/4/2/100814207.html?coluid=6&kindid=26&docid=100814207&mdate=1129102451|title=中國評論新聞網|website=Chinareviewnews.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="news.sina.com.tw">{{cite web|url=http://news.sina.com.tw/books/novel/barticle/3409.html|title=晚清的財富精英：1834年的世界首富-閱讀-新浪新聞中心|website=News.sina.com.tw|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>
==Biography== Born in [[Quanzhou]], [[Fujian]], China, he was known to the West as ''Howqua'' (the second). His father, Wu Guorong was also ''Howqua'' (the first) and was founder of the family company. Because his Chinese name was too difficult for western traders to pronounce,{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} the name Howqua comes from his Chinese Business Name "浩官" ({{zh|poj=Hō-koaⁿ}}), very similar to a [[Doing business as|DBA]].<ref>[[:zh:廣州十三行]]</ref> He became rich on the trade between China and the [[British Empire]] in the middle of the 19th century during the [[First Opium War]]. Perhaps the wealthiest man in China during the nineteenth century, Howqua was the senior of the Hong merchants in Canton, one of the few authorized to trade silk and porcelain with foreigners. According to historic records,<ref><<觸藩始末>> '''''The Start and End of Upsetting The Foreigners''''', Chapter 3</ref> there was a fire in 1822 and many of the [[cohong]]s were burned down. The melted silver allegedly formed a little stream almost two miles in length.<ref name="chinareviewnews.com"/><ref name="news.sina.com.tw"/> Of the 3 million dollars of compensation that was required to pay the British from the [[Treaty of Nanking]], he single-handedly contributed one million, one third of the total sum.<ref>[http://www.szdaj.gov.cn/dadg/rwzz/19.html 档案揭秘:被称为“天下第一大富翁”的伍秉鉴-欢迎进入深圳档案网<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He later died in [[Guangzhou|Canton]] the same year.
To this day, portraits of the pigtailed Howqua in his robes still hang in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]] and [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport mansions]] built by U.S. merchants grateful for his assistance.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}
==Legacy== During his time as one of the Hong merchants in the Thirteen Factories, under the [[Canton System]], the Qing Dynasty saw a short period of trade prosperity. [[Guangzhou|Canton]] also became one of the most populated cities in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geography.about.com/library/weekly/aa011201e.htm|title=What Were the Largest Cities Throughout History?|website=Geography.about.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>
The founders of then world-renowned firms including [[James Matheson]], [[William Jardine (merchant)|William Jardine]], [[Samuel Russell]] and [[Abiel Abbot Low]] all had a close relationship with Howqua. Following the 1842 [[Treaty of Nanking]], which spelled the end of the Thirteen Factories, [[Jardine Matheson Holdings|Jardine Matheson & Co]] continued to use "Ewo" as their Chinese name.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cheong|first=W.E.|title=The Hong merchants of Canton: Chinese merchants in Sino-Western trade|year=1997|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-7007-0361-6}} p.122 [https://books.google.com/books?id=3BjCHpQk5J8C&pg=PA122&lpg=PA122&dq=ewo+canton&source=bl&ots=QzmfVaeXMV&sig=0wawF7OPXXml_L8Vg_vBGlfTSBE&hl=zh-CN&ei=FyGiTbmICY_vcOizrPAB&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=ewo%20canton&f=false Online version at Google books]</ref>
With the spelling '''Hu-Kwa''', his name and likeness are used for a brand of imported [[lapsang souchong]] smoked [[tea]].
